1
00:00:00,870 --> 00:00:03,710
Speaker 21: Welcome to my talk on
modularizing a 10-year monolith.

2
00:00:03,910 --> 00:00:05,289
My name is Victor Luboslavsky.

3
00:00:05,289 --> 00:00:08,500
I've been in tech for over 25 years,
and I'm currently a principal software

4
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:10,119
engineer at Fleet Device Management.

5
00:00:10,500 --> 00:00:14,000
At Fleet, we make endpoint telemetry
for corporate security teams and device

6
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:15,539
management for corporate IT teams.

7
00:00:16,039 --> 00:00:19,670
In my current job, it took me roughly
a year to figure out the code base, get

8
00:00:19,670 --> 00:00:22,810
familiar with the programming language,
and understand our business domain.

9
00:00:23,410 --> 00:00:26,990
So around that time, I started to
notice a consistent issue whenever

10
00:00:26,990 --> 00:00:28,539
working on our service package.

11
00:00:29,039 --> 00:00:31,189
A package in Go is a compile unit.

12
00:00:31,689 --> 00:00:34,619
This service package was the
biggest one in our code base,

13
00:00:34,739 --> 00:00:39,200
and every time I recompiled its
tests, it took about 30 seconds.

14
00:00:39,419 --> 00:00:42,869
Even changing one character in
a string meant waiting again.

15
00:00:43,559 --> 00:00:45,520
That is a very specific kind of delay.

16
00:00:45,680 --> 00:00:49,750
It's not long enough to switch tasks,
and it's not short enough to ignore.

17
00:00:50,070 --> 00:00:51,980
It just interrupts your thinking.

18
00:00:52,410 --> 00:00:55,469
You wait, your attention drifts,
and then you have to load the

19
00:00:55,469 --> 00:00:57,399
problem in your head again.

20
00:00:57,910 --> 00:01:00,149
And that happens over and over.

21
00:01:00,649 --> 00:01:04,839
When your thinking loop breaks,
you lose context, and getting that

22
00:01:04,839 --> 00:01:06,789
context back is the expensive part.

23
00:01:07,379 --> 00:01:08,739
The wait is not the real problem.

24
00:01:08,779 --> 00:01:10,849
The problem is the
broken train of thought.

25
00:01:11,349 --> 00:01:12,479
So I did a little digging.

26
00:01:12,819 --> 00:01:15,509
The Go programming language is
known for fast compile times.

27
00:01:15,819 --> 00:01:20,499
However, the linking phase of the
compile still occurs largely in series.

28
00:01:21,019 --> 00:01:24,889
In my experiments tracing the build
process, most of that recompile was

29
00:01:24,889 --> 00:01:27,179
stuck waiting for a single thread.

30
00:01:27,669 --> 00:01:31,920
This means if we have a large number of
packages to link together, the linking

31
00:01:31,920 --> 00:01:33,999
phase will dominate the compile time.

32
00:01:34,539 --> 00:01:36,830
From this analysis, the issue was obvious.

33
00:01:37,010 --> 00:01:40,789
Our service package was too big
and had too many dependencies.

34
00:01:41,289 --> 00:01:42,959
So I asked myself a simple question.

35
00:01:43,629 --> 00:01:45,539
What am I actually trying to do here?

36
00:01:45,739 --> 00:01:49,459
I'm not trying to fight a build system
or wrestle with a giant package.

37
00:01:49,789 --> 00:01:51,389
I'm just trying to write good software.

38
00:01:52,369 --> 00:01:55,109
And it shouldn't take 30 seconds
of self-therapy every time

39
00:01:55,109 --> 00:01:56,389
I change a string literal.

40
00:01:56,889 --> 00:01:58,149
What about AI agents?

41
00:01:58,309 --> 00:02:00,569
They aren't as concerned about
waiting 30 seconds for the

42
00:02:00,569 --> 00:02:01,979
code and compile loop, right?

43
00:02:02,479 --> 00:02:06,019
So if I'm using an AI agent, I
can let it handle the coding while

44
00:02:06,019 --> 00:02:07,899
I switch to another task, right?

45
00:02:08,399 --> 00:02:09,959
That doesn't fully solve the problem.

46
00:02:10,519 --> 00:02:14,769
If I need to do a small code change, I
can do it faster than an agent right now.

47
00:02:15,269 --> 00:02:17,899
This means using an AI agent
for some tasks will actually

48
00:02:17,899 --> 00:02:19,129
slow me down even more.

49
00:02:19,649 --> 00:02:24,879
Second, if an AI agent-- second, an
AI agent often runs the test cycle

50
00:02:24,879 --> 00:02:27,239
way more times than a human developer.

51
00:02:27,749 --> 00:02:30,369
And in our case, the
tests are the bottleneck.

52
00:02:31,189 --> 00:02:34,379
So it's arguably even more
important to reduce the compile

53
00:02:34,379 --> 00:02:36,719
time to speed up our AI friends.

54
00:02:37,219 --> 00:02:40,729
So if I just wanna write good
software, what needs to change?

55
00:02:41,279 --> 00:02:45,639
I want a code base that feels light,
understandable, and fast, one that helps

56
00:02:45,639 --> 00:02:47,629
me think instead of slowing me down.

57
00:02:48,119 --> 00:02:52,549
And I realized the only way to get there
was to make the code base itself smaller.

58
00:02:53,259 --> 00:02:55,039
So we tried modularizing.

59
00:02:55,539 --> 00:02:59,109
Next, let's discuss our first
attempt at modularization, where,

60
00:02:59,139 --> 00:03:03,029
as you might guess, things didn't
quite go as smooth as we hoped.

61
00:03:03,529 --> 00:03:04,659
Let's talk about our code base.

62
00:03:05,069 --> 00:03:08,369
Fleet Device Management is
primarily MIT licensed open source.

63
00:03:08,659 --> 00:03:12,299
We also maintain a small set of
advanced features in a clearly separated

64
00:03:12,299 --> 00:03:13,779
directory under a different license.

65
00:03:14,209 --> 00:03:18,029
Our code base is roughly ten years
old with about eight hundred thousand

66
00:03:18,029 --> 00:03:20,209
lines of Go code and growing.

67
00:03:20,709 --> 00:03:23,639
This is a much simplified picture
of the core of our service layer.

68
00:03:24,039 --> 00:03:27,479
We have a su- single huge Go
package for the API layer.

69
00:03:27,679 --> 00:03:28,739
It's our service package.

70
00:03:28,989 --> 00:03:32,209
It includes controllers and the
service containing our business logic.

71
00:03:32,579 --> 00:03:34,809
This API layer calls
the persistence layer.

72
00:03:35,109 --> 00:03:37,609
The persistence layer is
another huge Go package.

73
00:03:37,889 --> 00:03:42,359
It constructs the SQL queries and
executes them against our MySQL database.

74
00:03:43,159 --> 00:03:47,249
We also have an in-memory cache, a React
front end, a CLI, and a bunch of smaller

75
00:03:47,249 --> 00:03:49,289
components which are not pictured here.

76
00:03:49,789 --> 00:03:53,939
So at one of our engineering all hand-
hands meetings, I gave a presentation.

77
00:03:54,209 --> 00:03:58,739
I described how we could scale our code
base to a more modular architecture.

78
00:03:59,239 --> 00:04:02,289
The core idea of my presentation
was that when working on a major

79
00:04:02,289 --> 00:04:07,089
new feature, we could create a
new module, a vertical slice.

80
00:04:07,929 --> 00:04:12,319
This new vertical slice would mirror
the structure of the legacy code.

81
00:04:12,699 --> 00:04:15,479
We would organize it exactly
like the legacy code.

82
00:04:15,749 --> 00:04:18,659
That way, engineers would still
roughly know where things are.

83
00:04:19,159 --> 00:04:22,399
This actually looks exactly
like a microservice, but still

84
00:04:22,399 --> 00:04:24,410
within a single compiled binary.

85
00:04:24,910 --> 00:04:28,320
The presentation seems to land,
and I felt confident enough

86
00:04:28,320 --> 00:04:30,010
to try it on a real feature.

87
00:04:30,630 --> 00:04:32,780
We have some smart engineers
on the team, so I felt like I

88
00:04:32,780 --> 00:04:34,520
was going down the right path.

89
00:04:35,110 --> 00:04:37,060
I did get one question
that I wanna mention.

90
00:04:37,560 --> 00:04:41,900
The question was, "If the team
structure changes, do we have to

91
00:04:41,980 --> 00:04:44,959
redo the architecture?" Maybe.

92
00:04:45,529 --> 00:04:49,480
The boundaries still need to make
sense in the product and the domain,

93
00:04:50,169 --> 00:04:53,270
but they don't need to have a
one-to-one match with the org chart.

94
00:04:53,620 --> 00:04:57,800
A single team can own several slices,
and if that team later splits,

95
00:04:57,800 --> 00:04:59,809
those splice slices can split too.

96
00:05:00,309 --> 00:05:04,099
Shortly afterwards, we started working
on a new feature, and this new feature

97
00:05:04,099 --> 00:05:08,069
seemed like the ideal candidate to
try this new modularization approach.

98
00:05:08,489 --> 00:05:11,239
The feature was Android MDM,
Mobile Device Management.

99
00:05:11,609 --> 00:05:17,339
It meant a new hardware platform for us to
support using a new, for us, Google API.

100
00:05:17,839 --> 00:05:20,039
I created the new structure
for the Android support.

101
00:05:20,209 --> 00:05:22,619
I created new packages
in a dedicated directory.

102
00:05:23,079 --> 00:05:26,399
Most of the work was actually untangling
some common por- parts so they

103
00:05:26,399 --> 00:05:30,429
could be reused between the legacy
code and this new Android feature.

104
00:05:30,929 --> 00:05:35,179
I put up the PR, the pull
request, and it just sat there.

105
00:05:35,599 --> 00:05:39,279
Our guidance is to review and merge
PRs within twenty-four hours, but

106
00:05:39,279 --> 00:05:41,169
no one wanted to touch this one.

107
00:05:41,999 --> 00:05:45,329
In retrospect, I should have done a
better job communicating to the team

108
00:05:45,639 --> 00:05:49,559
that I was actually going to do what
I proposed in my earlier presentation.

109
00:05:50,229 --> 00:05:52,559
Some engineers felt
surprised by the changes.

110
00:05:52,659 --> 00:05:55,169
They didn't feel like they
had a voice in this approach.

111
00:05:55,659 --> 00:05:57,669
They didn't have an
opportunity to speak up.

112
00:05:57,929 --> 00:06:00,939
So facing this resistance, I backtracked.

113
00:06:01,439 --> 00:06:04,219
Let's take a look at these
two MySQL databases down here.

114
00:06:04,669 --> 00:06:09,029
Having two MySQL schemas made
our migrations more complicated.

115
00:06:09,419 --> 00:06:13,159
It also made it impossible to
join tables across schemas.

116
00:06:13,659 --> 00:06:17,919
Even if we put both schemas into the same
physical database, it still would have

117
00:06:17,919 --> 00:06:19,799
made our deployments more complicated.

118
00:06:20,299 --> 00:06:23,229
We'll talk about this later in the
presentation, but at this point in the

119
00:06:23,229 --> 00:06:29,549
story, I decided to take a step back
and unsplit, unsplit the MySQL layer.

120
00:06:29,889 --> 00:06:33,859
So all requests would still
go to the same MySQL schema.

121
00:06:34,359 --> 00:06:38,099
Then I had several lengthy conversations
with my PR reviewer regarding the

122
00:06:38,099 --> 00:06:43,719
overall approach, and after a few more
minor adjustments, we merged the PR.

123
00:06:44,219 --> 00:06:49,059
A few weeks later, we also instituted an
ADR, architecture decision record process.

124
00:06:49,649 --> 00:06:53,499
This mens- this meant I needed to
create ADRs and retroactively get

125
00:06:53,499 --> 00:06:56,459
approval for these architecture changes.

126
00:06:56,959 --> 00:07:01,489
I wrote two ADRs, one to split the API
layer and one to split the persistence

127
00:07:01,489 --> 00:07:03,149
layer of the Android feature.

128
00:07:03,529 --> 00:07:07,629
The ADR to s- to split the API layer
was approved, but the ADR to split

129
00:07:07,629 --> 00:07:10,279
the persistence layer was rejected.

130
00:07:10,779 --> 00:07:15,189
Engineers voiced their concerns, which
included, " We've had this structure for

131
00:07:15,189 --> 00:07:16,999
a while, and people know how it works.

132
00:07:17,039 --> 00:07:18,469
Why do we need this change?

133
00:07:18,629 --> 00:07:22,519
It might confuse and slow people down."
" With separate persistence layers,

134
00:07:22,519 --> 00:07:27,069
it'll be much harder to do database
transactions across two separate modules."

135
00:07:27,569 --> 00:07:30,289
And, "This change is just too big.

136
00:07:30,739 --> 00:07:34,609
Let's try something incremental,
like splitting the API layer only.

137
00:07:34,609 --> 00:07:38,099
We can split the persistence layer
later." Their feedback was consistent.

138
00:07:38,509 --> 00:07:42,559
This felt risky, confusing,
and too big to do all at once.

139
00:07:43,059 --> 00:07:45,989
So I reverted the
persistence layer changes.

140
00:07:46,459 --> 00:07:50,919
The new API layer now talk to the
same large persistence package

141
00:07:50,999 --> 00:07:52,539
as the rest of the code base.

142
00:07:53,039 --> 00:07:55,309
And at this point, I actually
moved off this feature.

143
00:07:55,349 --> 00:07:56,869
I moved to help another product team.

144
00:07:56,899 --> 00:08:01,169
I worked on other parts of the code base,
and other engineers continued to work on

145
00:08:01,169 --> 00:08:05,465
this Android part of the code base We as a
company had a lot of features promised to

146
00:08:05,465 --> 00:08:09,345
our customers, so we were all moving very
quickly trying to get these features out.

147
00:08:09,845 --> 00:08:11,995
But this took a toll on our architecture.

148
00:08:12,185 --> 00:08:15,485
Without architectural oversight,
without a strong commitment from

149
00:08:15,485 --> 00:08:20,615
the engineering team, this Android
feature seeped into the legacy code.

150
00:08:21,345 --> 00:08:23,165
So what do we have now?

151
00:08:23,665 --> 00:08:26,335
The picture shows roughly what we have.

152
00:08:26,625 --> 00:08:30,825
Certainly, at a high level, the code
base doesn't appear to be very modular.

153
00:08:31,375 --> 00:08:35,075
Arguably, it's even more complex and
harder to maintain than it was before.

154
00:08:35,805 --> 00:08:39,905
In practice, there's really no
clear separation between the legacy

155
00:08:39,905 --> 00:08:41,555
code and the Android feature.

156
00:08:42,055 --> 00:08:43,595
But it's not all bad news.

157
00:08:43,685 --> 00:08:45,085
Some positives do remain.

158
00:08:45,635 --> 00:08:49,935
Most Android-specific controllers are
in a separate package, which makes

159
00:08:49,935 --> 00:08:51,695
it easier to change and reason about.

160
00:08:52,265 --> 00:08:55,305
Some Android-specific code is
now isolated, which accelerates

161
00:08:55,305 --> 00:08:59,035
development and testing within
that Android service package.

162
00:08:59,575 --> 00:09:04,615
And not shown here, we did break apart
some common code out of the legacy

163
00:09:04,615 --> 00:09:09,775
service package, which makes it easier
to create new API layers in the future.

164
00:09:10,275 --> 00:09:14,245
Next, let's discuss what we've
learned from our first attempt.

165
00:09:14,745 --> 00:09:18,025
I keep rediscovering that
talking to people takes time,

166
00:09:18,695 --> 00:09:19,765
and there's no shortcut.

167
00:09:20,145 --> 00:09:20,925
Real time.

168
00:09:21,445 --> 00:09:24,965
Meetings, follow-ups, side
conversations, and the bigger the

169
00:09:24,965 --> 00:09:28,075
organization, the slower that loop gets.

170
00:09:28,875 --> 00:09:31,525
We also can't rely on who speaks up first.

171
00:09:31,835 --> 00:09:34,685
Early voices are often smart
and well-intentioned, but

172
00:09:34,685 --> 00:09:36,365
they don't represent everyone.

173
00:09:36,715 --> 00:09:41,675
To build real consensus, we have to
actively solicit feedback, especially

174
00:09:41,675 --> 00:09:43,605
in one-on-ones and smaller forums.

175
00:09:44,105 --> 00:09:48,585
To succeed, we need strong commitment,
both from the engineers and managers,

176
00:09:49,245 --> 00:09:53,285
to the architecture and to the
specific boundaries we are proposing.

177
00:09:54,045 --> 00:09:58,135
Without that commitment, engineers
naturally revert to old patterns and

178
00:09:58,135 --> 00:10:00,725
architectural compromises creep back in.

179
00:10:01,275 --> 00:10:04,555
And without management support,
short-term delivery pressure

180
00:10:04,555 --> 00:10:07,345
wins over long-term structure.

181
00:10:07,845 --> 00:10:10,495
Let's give a small example
of misunderstanding.

182
00:10:11,115 --> 00:10:14,135
In one case, people were
confused about the words.

183
00:10:14,665 --> 00:10:16,425
I was using the term modules.

184
00:10:16,985 --> 00:10:21,365
I was using it in an architectural
sense to mean a cohesive group

185
00:10:21,365 --> 00:10:23,175
of code with a clear boundary.

186
00:10:23,875 --> 00:10:28,085
However, some people thought I was
talking about Go modules, which

187
00:10:28,085 --> 00:10:31,045
is a way to distribute packages
in the Go programming language.

188
00:10:31,545 --> 00:10:32,365
Nobody was wrong.

189
00:10:32,395 --> 00:10:35,545
We just weren't talking about
the same thing, and it took a

190
00:10:35,545 --> 00:10:37,395
face-to-face meeting to sort this out.

191
00:10:37,895 --> 00:10:39,935
We thought the hard part
was the architecture.

192
00:10:39,975 --> 00:10:42,545
It turned out the hard part
were the conversations.

193
00:10:43,045 --> 00:10:44,396
Let's move on to the second lesson.

194
00:10:45,326 --> 00:10:47,465
What is an architectural change anyway?

195
00:10:48,265 --> 00:10:51,245
That sounds like a straightforward
question, but in practice, it

196
00:10:51,245 --> 00:10:55,485
turns out to be one of the most
political questions in engineering.

197
00:10:55,985 --> 00:10:57,325
Here's what we saw in reality.

198
00:10:57,895 --> 00:11:00,955
Architectur- architectural
changes in our code base rarely

199
00:11:00,955 --> 00:11:03,045
showed up as architecture work.

200
00:11:03,505 --> 00:11:06,305
Instead, they went in
as part of feature work.

201
00:11:06,805 --> 00:11:11,476
If you framed your change as part of
feature work and included it in a PR with

202
00:11:11,506 --> 00:11:16,855
other feature changes, it moved, even if
it broke existing architectural patterns.

203
00:11:17,406 --> 00:11:20,025
After all, we needed to get all
the feature changes in quickly.

204
00:11:20,385 --> 00:11:22,226
Features are what make
money for the company.

205
00:11:22,736 --> 00:11:25,625
But if you framed your change
as a standalone architectural

206
00:11:25,625 --> 00:11:28,006
improvement, it stalled.

207
00:11:28,215 --> 00:11:31,026
It stalled because it was
prioritized behind feature work.

208
00:11:31,206 --> 00:11:34,245
It stalled because engineers wanted
to have bigger discussions around it.

209
00:11:34,646 --> 00:11:38,255
It stalled because it wasn't providing
immediate value to the company.

210
00:11:38,755 --> 00:11:41,345
So what's the main lesson here
about architectural changes?

211
00:11:42,225 --> 00:11:47,315
If you don't define how your architecture
is allowed to change, it changes anyway,

212
00:11:47,835 --> 00:11:49,725
and often it changes behind your back.

213
00:11:50,685 --> 00:11:51,985
Let's move on to the third lesson.

214
00:11:52,485 --> 00:11:55,525
One thing we were missing
was clear ownership.

215
00:11:56,075 --> 00:11:59,505
In a modular system, not
every API endpoint belongs

216
00:11:59,505 --> 00:12:01,235
cleanly to a single service.

217
00:12:01,735 --> 00:12:06,015
Some endpoint mostly orchestrate
work across multiple services.

218
00:12:06,395 --> 00:12:09,805
That was true for us because this
new Android function- functionality

219
00:12:09,805 --> 00:12:12,435
still needed to talk to legacy code.

220
00:12:13,355 --> 00:12:16,635
The mistake was leaving
this orchestration unowned.

221
00:12:17,135 --> 00:12:22,215
Every API endpoint still needs a
clear home, a specific module, and a

222
00:12:22,215 --> 00:12:24,605
specific team that's responsible for it.

223
00:12:25,156 --> 00:12:29,795
Even if the endpoint is just glue,
someone has to own that glue.

224
00:12:30,295 --> 00:12:32,056
So where are we at this point?

225
00:12:32,816 --> 00:12:34,586
The first attempt didn't quite succeed.

226
00:12:34,865 --> 00:12:37,966
We still have the pain points of a
large, tightly coupled code base.

227
00:12:38,525 --> 00:12:41,016
But hopefully, we learned a few things.

228
00:12:41,516 --> 00:12:42,596
We now have experience.

229
00:12:43,426 --> 00:12:45,026
So where do we go from here?

230
00:12:45,526 --> 00:12:48,816
At this point, I realized the
importance of the people part in

231
00:12:48,816 --> 00:12:52,966
architecture, and I felt like I
couldn't convince the company on my own.

232
00:12:53,545 --> 00:12:55,706
I still didn't feel like
an architecture expert.

233
00:12:56,045 --> 00:12:59,806
The first attempt was a mess, so
why would other engineers take my

234
00:12:59,806 --> 00:13:04,336
next proposal seriously and not
see it as just another crazy idea?

235
00:13:04,996 --> 00:13:06,826
I needed someone else's help.

236
00:13:07,236 --> 00:13:09,866
I needed something like
an appeal to authority.

237
00:13:10,276 --> 00:13:15,286
I needed to find someone else that had
already done this transition, and I needed

238
00:13:15,286 --> 00:13:17,056
to analyze the way they approached it.

239
00:13:17,556 --> 00:13:22,156
Unfortunately, I did not find any
large open source Go projects making

240
00:13:22,156 --> 00:13:24,576
a transition to a modular monolith.

241
00:13:25,386 --> 00:13:29,356
As far as I know, we're the first large
open source Go project doing this.

242
00:13:29,726 --> 00:13:30,426
Yay us.

243
00:13:31,356 --> 00:13:33,716
The next best reference was GitLab.

244
00:13:34,216 --> 00:13:37,286
GitLab runs a Ruby on Rails
monolith with over two million

245
00:13:37,286 --> 00:13:41,546
lines of code maintained by a large
distributed engineering organization.

246
00:13:42,176 --> 00:13:45,866
They faced the same decision we
were facing, whether to break

247
00:13:45,866 --> 00:13:49,156
everything into microservices
or find another way to scale.

248
00:13:49,696 --> 00:13:52,016
They deliberately chose
a modular monolith.

249
00:13:52,616 --> 00:13:56,516
GitLab publicly documented this decision,
and their motivation was practical.

250
00:13:56,936 --> 00:14:00,016
They wanted to avoid the operational
complexity of microservices,

251
00:14:00,346 --> 00:14:03,556
and they wanted to keep the code
base approachable for engineers.

252
00:14:04,056 --> 00:14:08,466
And they wanted to use clear domain
boundaries to scale development safely.

253
00:14:09,176 --> 00:14:12,786
Their example showed that modularity
and scale don't require microservices.

254
00:14:13,126 --> 00:14:16,426
And to us, it showed that
a large successful team had

255
00:14:16,426 --> 00:14:18,326
already walked this same path.

256
00:14:18,696 --> 00:14:23,836
And it turned my proposal from a
crazy idea into a proven pattern.

257
00:14:24,376 --> 00:14:26,266
We weren't trying to invent something new.

258
00:14:26,486 --> 00:14:29,836
We were trying to follow a
trail that was already there.

259
00:14:30,336 --> 00:14:32,326
Internally, that changed the conversation.

260
00:14:32,746 --> 00:14:35,446
Before that, the conversation
kept circling about whether this

261
00:14:35,446 --> 00:14:39,856
was too unusual, too risky, or
too academic for our code base.

262
00:14:40,396 --> 00:14:44,256
GitLab gave us a reference point
that was concrete, public, and

263
00:14:44,256 --> 00:14:45,886
large enough to be taken seriously.

264
00:14:46,556 --> 00:14:49,786
It didn't answer all of our questions,
but it changed the burden of proof.

265
00:14:50,556 --> 00:14:55,366
I no longer had to argue that
modularization was some novel idea or

266
00:14:55,366 --> 00:14:57,236
personal preference we should gamble on.

267
00:14:57,476 --> 00:15:02,426
I could point to a real company with a
larger monolith than ours that had already

268
00:15:02,426 --> 00:15:05,396
made this same bet for practical reasons.

269
00:15:05,896 --> 00:15:08,176
Next, we had to decide where to start.

270
00:15:08,826 --> 00:15:11,926
This time, there was no obvious
feature to use as an anchor.

271
00:15:12,426 --> 00:15:15,766
So we had a series of discussions
with the engineering team.

272
00:15:16,046 --> 00:15:19,986
We aligned on bounded context and
domain-driven design in principle.

273
00:15:20,316 --> 00:15:23,196
The hard part was choosing
that first boundary.

274
00:15:23,696 --> 00:15:27,146
I looked at our code organization
and had a few conversations with my

275
00:15:27,146 --> 00:15:31,796
AI agent friend and proposed several
ways we could slice the monolith.

276
00:15:32,296 --> 00:15:36,106
As you can imagine, this whole process
was a lot to get your head around,

277
00:15:36,106 --> 00:15:40,176
trying to tease apart a 10-year-old
system into self-contained modules.

278
00:15:40,676 --> 00:15:42,956
I felt like I was barely
scratching the surface.

279
00:15:43,216 --> 00:15:46,516
I felt like I was surely missing
a lot of details and edge cases.

280
00:15:46,926 --> 00:15:48,606
There were a lot of unknowns.

281
00:15:48,996 --> 00:15:51,486
Starting our modularization
effort with anything beyond

282
00:15:51,486 --> 00:15:53,336
the bare minimum seemed risky.

283
00:15:53,956 --> 00:15:57,536
All the engineers generally agreed that
we wanted to do an incremental approach.

284
00:15:58,036 --> 00:16:02,206
So we ultimately agreed on this
activity and audit over here.

285
00:16:02,866 --> 00:16:05,996
This content is- context is
about recording things that

286
00:16:05,996 --> 00:16:07,336
already happened in our system.

287
00:16:07,686 --> 00:16:11,306
For example, recording when a new user
was created, when a new host enrolled,

288
00:16:11,306 --> 00:16:15,386
when a key configuration was changed,
and a ton o- of other activities.

289
00:16:15,886 --> 00:16:19,296
Next, I wrote up a detailed
architectural decision record and

290
00:16:19,296 --> 00:16:20,876
put it up for review by the team.

291
00:16:21,376 --> 00:16:24,366
Here's the link in case someone
can't wait to dive into the details.

292
00:16:24,886 --> 00:16:27,416
Again, this ADR was framed as a pilot.

293
00:16:27,776 --> 00:16:31,626
This is the first bounded context we
were creating before a bigger rollout.

294
00:16:32,126 --> 00:16:33,966
The ADR was up for review for a while.

295
00:16:34,466 --> 00:16:36,926
We discussed it multiple
times in multiple meetings.

296
00:16:37,456 --> 00:16:42,076
For me, I just wanted to start
coding, so I felt quite uncomfortable

297
00:16:42,076 --> 00:16:44,636
to be stuck in that waiting limbo.

298
00:16:45,476 --> 00:16:49,286
Instead, I got another lesson regarding
the importance of interpersonal

299
00:16:49,286 --> 00:16:51,146
skill in software architecture.

300
00:16:51,646 --> 00:16:53,946
Most of the feedback I got was good.

301
00:16:54,186 --> 00:16:56,306
We have very smart
engineers, and that showed.

302
00:16:57,236 --> 00:17:02,526
What made it hard wasn't bad feedback,
it was the volume of it and the timing.

303
00:17:03,186 --> 00:17:06,456
Sometimes feedback came faster I-
than I could realistically absorb.

304
00:17:07,196 --> 00:17:09,506
"Have you checked in with so and
should we run an event storming

305
00:17:09,506 --> 00:17:14,026
session? Can you do this other thing?"
All reasonable suggestions, all

306
00:17:14,026 --> 00:17:15,866
well-intentioned, but they added weight.

307
00:17:16,366 --> 00:17:19,056
Then a few times, the
feedback landed late.

308
00:17:19,436 --> 00:17:24,766
Things like, "Whoa, can we step back
and think about the bigger picture?"

309
00:17:25,266 --> 00:17:29,296
That's an important question, it just
would have been easier earlier in the

310
00:17:29,296 --> 00:17:33,536
discussions before trying to slice up
the monolith, before the ADR went up.

311
00:17:34,176 --> 00:17:38,746
At that point, we were already six
weeks in, momentum was building, and

312
00:17:38,816 --> 00:17:41,426
it felt like being asked to rewind.

313
00:17:41,926 --> 00:17:45,646
This ended up being a good exercise
in patience, mostly for me.

314
00:17:46,486 --> 00:17:52,296
Often, my best response was, "Okay, that's
interesting. I'll think about it," then

315
00:17:52,296 --> 00:17:56,776
take a break, calm down, and come back
to the feedback in a better head space.

316
00:17:57,276 --> 00:18:00,606
Several times, I wondered where this
whole thing was gonna go anywhere.

317
00:18:01,076 --> 00:18:03,036
Sometimes it felt like
everyone was on board.

318
00:18:03,066 --> 00:18:05,946
Other times, it felt like I
kept running into a brick wall.

319
00:18:06,446 --> 00:18:08,936
It felt like I kept bringing
people along with the plan, and

320
00:18:08,936 --> 00:18:10,936
then they slowly drifted away.

321
00:18:11,336 --> 00:18:14,116
It felt like I kept grabbing people
to get them on my side, and then

322
00:18:14,116 --> 00:18:15,746
they slipped out of my hands.

323
00:18:16,246 --> 00:18:21,986
I also felt I was deep in the weeds
and details of this re-architecture.

324
00:18:22,016 --> 00:18:26,486
I didn't quite see the full picture
myself, and I had a suspicion

325
00:18:26,516 --> 00:18:28,436
other engineers didn't either.

326
00:18:29,406 --> 00:18:35,316
I actually needed to convince myself and
others why we were actually doing this.

327
00:18:35,816 --> 00:18:41,576
I needed an argument, and I needed to use
it not just once, but every chance I got.

328
00:18:42,076 --> 00:18:45,846
That's when I finally started to
understand that old management maxim.

329
00:18:46,086 --> 00:18:49,896
By the time you're tired of saying it,
people are just starting to hear it.

330
00:18:50,396 --> 00:18:52,456
This picture is from
the 1970 movie Pattern.

331
00:18:53,216 --> 00:18:55,876
So here, roughly, is my
argument for the team.

332
00:18:56,376 --> 00:18:59,106
Yes, this is a brief talk
I've given to the team.

333
00:18:59,756 --> 00:19:02,136
It's supposed to be somewhat
motivational in nature.

334
00:19:02,636 --> 00:19:03,326
All right, team.

335
00:19:03,816 --> 00:19:05,146
Here's why we're doing this.

336
00:19:05,666 --> 00:19:08,046
Our backend is around 800,000 lines of Go.

337
00:19:08,466 --> 00:19:10,166
That number by itself is not the problem.

338
00:19:10,296 --> 00:19:13,076
The problem is what it does
to day-to-day engineering.

339
00:19:13,576 --> 00:19:17,406
At this size, you stop working
in clean, isolated areas of code.

340
00:19:17,896 --> 00:19:22,146
More and more often, different teams end
up in the same database tables, the same

341
00:19:22,146 --> 00:19:24,116
service layer, the same shared logic.

342
00:19:24,846 --> 00:19:28,426
GitLab, Shopify, and others have written
about these scaling issues publicly.

343
00:19:29,046 --> 00:19:32,336
We're seeing this same
pattern in our own codebase.

344
00:19:33,326 --> 00:19:36,376
First, teams start
colliding with each other.

345
00:19:36,676 --> 00:19:39,946
We've already had cases where two
groups changed the same tables or the

346
00:19:39,946 --> 00:19:44,186
same service code without realizing
how tightly connected those areas were.

347
00:19:44,646 --> 00:19:46,126
The cleanup took days.

348
00:19:46,556 --> 00:19:49,496
Not because anyone was careless,
because the boundaries were

349
00:19:49,496 --> 00:19:51,226
weak, the ownership was blurry.

350
00:19:52,186 --> 00:19:55,116
When that happens, the cost
is not just merge conflict.

351
00:19:55,536 --> 00:19:59,926
It is rework, regressions, and
time spent figuring out who is

352
00:19:59,926 --> 00:20:01,496
actually responsible for what.

353
00:20:01,996 --> 00:20:05,716
Second, the cost of a small
change keeps going up.

354
00:20:06,256 --> 00:20:10,116
When packages depend on too much
around them, even a modest change

355
00:20:10,116 --> 00:20:12,226
pulls in unrelated context.

356
00:20:12,836 --> 00:20:16,866
Reviews get slower, testing gets
noisier, the chance of side effects

357
00:20:16,866 --> 00:20:19,726
goes up, bugs become harder to isolate.

358
00:20:20,106 --> 00:20:22,346
At some point, the system is
no longer difficult because

359
00:20:22,346 --> 00:20:24,076
one part is especially complex.

360
00:20:24,276 --> 00:20:27,636
It is difficult because too many
parts are connected to each other.

361
00:20:28,136 --> 00:20:31,046
That is the problem
modularization is meant to solve.

362
00:20:31,616 --> 00:20:34,906
Not elegance, not trend
following, containment.

363
00:20:35,376 --> 00:20:39,546
Smaller areas of code, clear ownership,
fewer reasons for different teams

364
00:20:39,546 --> 00:20:41,156
to touch the same lines of code.

365
00:20:41,636 --> 00:20:45,146
If a team can make a change without
loading half the system into their heads,

366
00:20:45,566 --> 00:20:47,766
they move faster and with less risk.

367
00:20:48,026 --> 00:20:49,746
That is the outcome we want.

368
00:20:50,246 --> 00:20:52,776
So this is not architecture
for its own sake.

369
00:20:53,036 --> 00:20:55,836
It is a response to cost
we're already paying.

370
00:20:56,066 --> 00:20:59,846
Bug escapes, long reviews, features
taking too long to land, and

371
00:20:59,846 --> 00:21:01,726
fixes that need follow-up fixes.

372
00:21:02,196 --> 00:21:05,446
We can keep treating those as
separate incidents, or we can

373
00:21:05,446 --> 00:21:08,776
admit that the structure of the
system is part of the problem.

374
00:21:09,166 --> 00:21:10,866
That is why we're doing this.

375
00:21:11,741 --> 00:21:15,611
Our code base is 10 years old, and we
expect it to be around a lot longer.

376
00:21:16,101 --> 00:21:21,431
This work is about making sure the code
base helps engineers build instead of

377
00:21:21,431 --> 00:21:25,501
getting in their way, not by rewriting
the system, not by breaking into the

378
00:21:25,501 --> 00:21:31,151
microservices, by introducing boundaries
we can actually maintain as the product

379
00:21:31,151 --> 00:21:32,801
and the company continue to grow.

380
00:21:33,301 --> 00:21:34,521
And end scene.

381
00:21:35,021 --> 00:21:37,221
Now, let's talk about
the actual architecture.

382
00:21:37,721 --> 00:21:41,631
The high-level idea is almost the same as
where we started with the first attempt.

383
00:21:42,341 --> 00:21:45,331
The new feature or new bounded
context will be in its own

384
00:21:45,331 --> 00:21:48,431
module with its own controller,
service, and persistence layers.

385
00:21:49,191 --> 00:21:52,141
The controllers and services will
be able to call methods on other

386
00:21:52,141 --> 00:21:54,041
services in other bounded contexts.

387
00:21:54,041 --> 00:21:57,731
However, they will not be able
to access the persistence layer

388
00:21:57,931 --> 00:21:59,151
of another bounded context.

389
00:21:59,651 --> 00:22:04,101
In practical terms, that means a
bounded context can call another context

390
00:22:04,101 --> 00:22:09,271
public service API, but it cannot
reach into that context data store

391
00:22:09,591 --> 00:22:11,231
just because that would be convenient.

392
00:22:11,961 --> 00:22:15,441
Once one context starts reading
or writing another context tables

393
00:22:15,441 --> 00:22:19,351
through its internal persistence
code, the boundary is mostly gone.

394
00:22:19,351 --> 00:22:22,731
At that point, the ownership looks
clean in the directory structure, but

395
00:22:22,731 --> 00:22:24,991
not in the behavior of the system.

396
00:22:25,491 --> 00:22:29,601
Here's the directory layout of the
bounded context, and we'll bring up

397
00:22:29,601 --> 00:22:31,721
this slide a couple times later as well.

398
00:22:31,981 --> 00:22:37,051
So the service and MySQL
directories over here match the

399
00:22:37,051 --> 00:22:39,901
API layer and the persistence
layer from the previous diagram.

400
00:22:40,641 --> 00:22:47,731
The integration test over here should
be able to fully test this bounded

401
00:22:47,731 --> 00:22:51,511
context without requiring parts
from the rest of the application.

402
00:22:52,011 --> 00:22:55,611
Now, testing this bounded context with
other bounded context will be done

403
00:22:55,611 --> 00:22:57,761
at a higher-level integration test.

404
00:22:58,261 --> 00:23:02,491
Another detail that mattered is what
the bounded context does not own.

405
00:23:03,171 --> 00:23:06,451
It does not own authentication
or authorization, for example.

406
00:23:06,811 --> 00:23:08,631
Those are injected from the outside.

407
00:23:09,211 --> 00:23:12,591
Authentication comes in as
middleware at the HTTP layer.

408
00:23:12,811 --> 00:23:16,251
Authorization comes in as a
dependency the service can call

409
00:23:16,291 --> 00:23:17,731
but does not implement itself.

410
00:23:18,231 --> 00:23:22,751
That separation kept the context
focused on its own domain instead

411
00:23:22,751 --> 00:23:26,171
of absorbing cross-cutting concerns
just because they were already

412
00:23:26,171 --> 00:23:27,471
present elsewhere in the monolith.

413
00:23:28,441 --> 00:23:31,771
Now, let's talk about the decision
not to split the database schema.

414
00:23:32,271 --> 00:23:35,501
When people hear modular
monolith, they often assume

415
00:23:35,501 --> 00:23:37,131
that means multiple databases.

416
00:23:37,591 --> 00:23:39,211
We deliberately did not do that.

417
00:23:39,261 --> 00:23:40,961
We kept a single schema.

418
00:23:41,661 --> 00:23:45,731
Our problems weren't database scale
or load, they were unclear ownership,

419
00:23:45,731 --> 00:23:49,051
broad service layers, and code
that was too hard to reason about.

420
00:23:49,621 --> 00:23:51,831
Splitting the database
wouldn't have fixed that.

421
00:23:52,161 --> 00:23:56,736
It just would have made operational
complexity Added operation

422
00:23:56,736 --> 00:23:58,306
complexity and new failure modes.

423
00:23:58,806 --> 00:24:02,436
Splitting a database is also one of the
most expensive architectural decisions

424
00:24:02,436 --> 00:24:04,896
you can make, and it freezes boundaries.

425
00:24:05,546 --> 00:24:09,946
We were still learning where those
boundaries should be, so we modularized

426
00:24:09,946 --> 00:24:14,406
the code first, preserved optionality,
and decided we'd only split the database

427
00:24:14,406 --> 00:24:17,226
later if scaling actually required it.

428
00:24:17,726 --> 00:24:22,836
Now, everywhere we turned, we heard
recommendations to use ports and adapters.

429
00:24:23,446 --> 00:24:29,086
However, a lot of our business logic
lives in SQL, so pretending a database is

430
00:24:29,086 --> 00:24:32,106
just an adapter didn't make sense for us.

431
00:24:32,796 --> 00:24:36,656
Ports and adapters doesn't work for our
whole sys- our system as a whole, but

432
00:24:36,656 --> 00:24:39,196
one idea from it fits extremely well.

433
00:24:39,866 --> 00:24:45,156
That idea is that bounded contexts do
not share the main models directly.

434
00:24:45,696 --> 00:24:50,376
Any cross-context communication must
go through an explicit owned contract.

435
00:24:50,876 --> 00:24:53,696
In practice, that means
explicit module boundaries.

436
00:24:54,566 --> 00:24:57,006
Earlier, I talked about how we
ended up with large packages.

437
00:24:57,506 --> 00:25:01,976
When the shared common package is
used for cross-context communication,

438
00:25:02,445 --> 00:25:04,136
it creates a specific problem.

439
00:25:04,586 --> 00:25:07,386
When two bounded contexts
share the same common types,

440
00:25:07,746 --> 00:25:09,076
they're no longer independent.

441
00:25:09,296 --> 00:25:12,676
A change in one context silently
changes the behavior of the other.

442
00:25:13,195 --> 00:25:16,816
At that point, the boundary only
exists in our heads, not in the code.

443
00:25:17,316 --> 00:25:20,776
For cross-context communication,
shared packages aren't reused.

444
00:25:20,905 --> 00:25:22,206
Instead, they're hidden coupling.

445
00:25:22,975 --> 00:25:27,596
That's why we require explicit owned
contracts at context boundaries.

446
00:25:28,096 --> 00:25:32,125
So when one bounded context
needs something from another, it

447
00:25:32,125 --> 00:25:33,415
doesn't reach into the internals.

448
00:25:33,415 --> 00:25:39,065
Instead, the providing context exposes
a small explicit interface along with

449
00:25:39,065 --> 00:25:41,855
the types that belong to this interface.

450
00:25:42,855 --> 00:25:45,975
Those interfaces and types
are owned by the provider.

451
00:25:46,125 --> 00:25:49,825
They live with the bounded context,
and they evolve on its terms.

452
00:25:50,425 --> 00:25:54,715
Other contexts can depend on the
contract but not on the implementation.

453
00:25:55,545 --> 00:25:59,595
That is what makes the boundary
real in code, not just in our heads.

454
00:26:00,095 --> 00:26:03,645
Now, sometimes, a new bounded
context still needs data or

455
00:26:03,645 --> 00:26:05,515
behavior that lives in legacy code.

456
00:26:06,015 --> 00:26:10,115
In those cases, we don't let the
new code talk to legacy directly.

457
00:26:10,635 --> 00:26:14,875
Instead, we introduce an anti-corruption
l- corruption layer, or ACL.

458
00:26:15,375 --> 00:26:19,085
The ACL is the only place
that understands both worlds.

459
00:26:19,705 --> 00:26:23,405
It translates legacy concepts,
types, and quirks into something the

460
00:26:23,405 --> 00:26:25,415
new context can work with safely.

461
00:26:26,225 --> 00:26:31,785
Now, notice that this ACL package is
outside the new bounded context, so that

462
00:26:31,785 --> 00:26:35,955
keeps the legacy semantics from leaking
into the new code, and it gives us a

463
00:26:35,955 --> 00:26:39,585
clear seam we can replace or delete later.

464
00:26:40,085 --> 00:26:43,315
The goal of this ACL isn't
elegance, it's containment.

465
00:26:44,305 --> 00:26:45,615
Now, let's continue with the story.

466
00:26:46,115 --> 00:26:50,375
Before we changed any code, we
had one big concern, buy-in.

467
00:26:50,975 --> 00:26:55,215
We didn't want this to feel like another
harebrained idea Victor came up with

468
00:26:55,215 --> 00:26:56,975
and everyone else has to live with.

469
00:26:57,625 --> 00:27:01,245
If this were going to work, our
software engineers needed to feel

470
00:27:01,405 --> 00:27:02,975
like the end result was theirs.

471
00:27:03,515 --> 00:27:07,515
Not something imposed, not
something slipped in quietly,

472
00:27:07,725 --> 00:27:09,715
something they actually owned.

473
00:27:10,215 --> 00:27:13,255
We left this ADR open for
discussion for about four weeks.

474
00:27:13,885 --> 00:27:16,435
That was longer than any
ADR we'd done before.

475
00:27:16,965 --> 00:27:19,975
We wanted time for people to
read it, question it, disagree

476
00:27:19,975 --> 00:27:21,565
with it, and sit with it.

477
00:27:22,065 --> 00:27:23,585
The goal wasn't fast approval.

478
00:27:23,805 --> 00:27:25,885
The goal was shared understanding.

479
00:27:26,385 --> 00:27:29,065
Next, we made a deliberate
decision about reviews.

480
00:27:29,655 --> 00:27:33,215
Every pull request related to this
ADR would be reviewed by the four

481
00:27:33,215 --> 00:27:34,655
tech leads from each product group.

482
00:27:35,275 --> 00:27:36,195
They did two things.

483
00:27:36,505 --> 00:27:40,215
First, it made sure they were
generally on board, the tech leads.

484
00:27:40,535 --> 00:27:45,615
Second, it meant their teams were
represented, not surprised later.

485
00:27:46,005 --> 00:27:49,085
Surprises are great for
birthdays, not for architecture.

486
00:27:49,895 --> 00:27:53,575
Architecture stopped being something
decided by one person and started being

487
00:27:53,575 --> 00:27:56,295
something carried by the organization.

488
00:27:56,795 --> 00:27:58,915
We also didn't want the
implementation to be rushed.

489
00:27:59,785 --> 00:28:03,705
The stories tied to this ADR went
through a normal design and spec process.

490
00:28:04,285 --> 00:28:07,475
And finally, we created a single
central page that tracked the

491
00:28:07,475 --> 00:28:09,585
status of all of this work.

492
00:28:10,545 --> 00:28:14,725
Anyone could see what was done, what was
in progress, and what was coming next.

493
00:28:15,285 --> 00:28:18,815
That visibility was important
because it turned a potentially risky

494
00:28:18,845 --> 00:28:22,985
architectural shift into a series
of small, understandable steps.

495
00:28:23,485 --> 00:28:27,995
At this point, it might seem like we
were putting a lot of process in place.

496
00:28:28,385 --> 00:28:31,185
Probably sounds like we were
saying, we need to have everything

497
00:28:31,185 --> 00:28:32,885
figured out before we even start.

498
00:28:33,795 --> 00:28:36,415
And to be honest, that
felt a little backwards.

499
00:28:36,875 --> 00:28:41,245
This is the first bounded context,
and it was supposed to be a pilot and

500
00:28:41,245 --> 00:28:43,085
not a well-engineered masterpiece.

501
00:28:43,405 --> 00:28:47,515
And a pilot is supposed to discover
things, which means sometimes taking

502
00:28:47,515 --> 00:28:51,115
a step forward only to backtrack
when things aren't working.

503
00:28:51,885 --> 00:28:56,015
If we already had all the answers, if
we were able to lay out all the steps

504
00:28:56,015 --> 00:29:00,015
in this refactoring top to bottom,
then we wouldn't need a pilot, right?

505
00:29:00,515 --> 00:29:04,965
This means we needed to do a POC,
a proof of concept, to discover

506
00:29:04,965 --> 00:29:06,975
things that we didn't know about.

507
00:29:07,475 --> 00:29:08,455
This was great for me.

508
00:29:08,785 --> 00:29:10,875
I love coding and I love POCs.

509
00:29:11,635 --> 00:29:15,505
The aim of the POC was to discover
things like which packages were

510
00:29:15,505 --> 00:29:17,655
coupled, which patterns to use where.

511
00:29:18,395 --> 00:29:19,935
Do we use shared objects?

512
00:29:20,005 --> 00:29:21,135
Do we use interfaces?

513
00:29:21,245 --> 00:29:22,535
Do we use async events?

514
00:29:23,135 --> 00:29:26,755
How will the communication between
bounded contexts actually look like?

515
00:29:27,515 --> 00:29:30,355
In order to make a plan,
we needed to know the path.

516
00:29:30,855 --> 00:29:33,105
So I started with a proof of concept.

517
00:29:33,665 --> 00:29:36,095
Not a full implementation,
just a scaffold.

518
00:29:36,565 --> 00:29:37,515
The idea was simple.

519
00:29:37,545 --> 00:29:40,185
Create some basic shape
of a bounded context.

520
00:29:40,575 --> 00:29:44,225
This means using some shared
utilities for HTTP, some middleware,

521
00:29:44,555 --> 00:29:47,575
basic MySQL access, nothing fancy.

522
00:29:48,035 --> 00:29:50,815
Just enough structure for
a hello world endpoint.

523
00:29:51,315 --> 00:29:55,885
Then I ran a dependency analysis, and
that's where things got interesting.

524
00:29:56,385 --> 00:30:01,865
That simple scaffold was
pulling in half our monolith.

525
00:30:02,805 --> 00:30:05,145
Not because this domain needed it.

526
00:30:05,365 --> 00:30:08,625
This hello world domain of the
scaffold didn't need anything yet.

527
00:30:09,155 --> 00:30:12,125
But because all of these
utility packages did.

528
00:30:12,845 --> 00:30:15,365
The glue code was the monolith.

529
00:30:15,735 --> 00:30:17,915
The things we thought were
harmless helpers were actually

530
00:30:17,915 --> 00:30:19,835
acting like dependency magnets.

531
00:30:20,825 --> 00:30:23,285
And there's another issue
hiding in plain sight.

532
00:30:23,785 --> 00:30:24,855
A god package.

533
00:30:25,355 --> 00:30:29,025
Anytime someone needed a new type and
didn't know where it belonged, it went

534
00:30:29,025 --> 00:30:31,155
into this fleet package at the bottom.

535
00:30:31,655 --> 00:30:36,805
And over time, that large fleet package
picked up its own dependencies, which

536
00:30:36,805 --> 00:30:38,275
were not shown in the previous slide.

537
00:30:38,305 --> 00:30:40,735
Otherwise, that slide would blow up.

538
00:30:41,055 --> 00:30:44,715
That meant everything that
imported it picked those up too.

539
00:30:45,455 --> 00:30:49,075
This made circular dependencies
incredibly easy to create and

540
00:30:49,075 --> 00:30:50,595
incredibly hard to understand.

541
00:30:51,465 --> 00:30:54,485
That fleet package existed
to make things easier, but it

542
00:30:54,515 --> 00:30:56,045
ended up doing the opposite.

543
00:30:56,545 --> 00:30:58,376
At that point, it became clear.

544
00:30:58,825 --> 00:31:01,605
We couldn't just extract a
bounded context right away.

545
00:31:01,795 --> 00:31:03,056
We were missing a layer.

546
00:31:03,666 --> 00:31:07,395
Before we could pull anything
out, we needed the platform layer.

547
00:31:08,315 --> 00:31:12,525
Code that handled infrastructure
concerns, HTTP helpers, database

548
00:31:12,525 --> 00:31:17,395
wiring, middleware, without dragging
domain assumptions along with it.

549
00:31:17,855 --> 00:31:20,395
We needed to differentiate
between two types of code.

550
00:31:21,016 --> 00:31:26,865
We needed domain code that should express
business rules and then platform code that

551
00:31:26,865 --> 00:31:29,405
should make those rules possible to run.

552
00:31:29,905 --> 00:31:34,486
So just to clarify, we do want
modules to reuse common code.

553
00:31:34,725 --> 00:31:37,736
We don't want every bounded
context team reinventing HTTP

554
00:31:37,736 --> 00:31:38,975
helpers or database plumbing.

555
00:31:39,566 --> 00:31:42,615
But reuse without
boundaries creates coupling.

556
00:31:42,916 --> 00:31:45,145
And coupling was the thing
we were trying to escape.

557
00:31:45,496 --> 00:31:49,566
Before we could modularize the domain,
we had to modularize the foundation.

558
00:31:50,066 --> 00:31:53,926
Another issue we had to solve from our
first attempt was that even with good

559
00:31:53,926 --> 00:31:59,626
communication, even with ADRs, even with
documentation, even with buy-in, nothing

560
00:31:59,626 --> 00:32:02,196
stops coupling from sneaking back in.

561
00:32:02,696 --> 00:32:06,276
Especially in a large code base, and
especially nowadays when changes aren't

562
00:32:06,306 --> 00:32:10,556
only written by humans, but also by AI
coding agents that optimize for make

563
00:32:10,556 --> 00:32:13,066
it work and not preserve architecture.

564
00:32:13,686 --> 00:32:16,736
Architecture that lives only in
people's heads doesn't scale,

565
00:32:16,976 --> 00:32:18,176
and it doesn't survive time.

566
00:32:18,676 --> 00:32:23,016
That's why we realized we needed
architectural checks, automated checks

567
00:32:23,016 --> 00:32:27,296
that run continuously, checks that don't
care who wrote the code, human or AI.

568
00:32:27,856 --> 00:32:32,266
Specifically, we needed checks to
enforce boundaries, which packages

569
00:32:32,266 --> 00:32:36,036
can depend on which, what the platform
layer is allowed to know, what a bounded

570
00:32:36,036 --> 00:32:38,116
context is not allowed to import.

571
00:32:38,556 --> 00:32:43,006
Because once those rules are explicit,
they stop being simply opinions.

572
00:32:43,006 --> 00:32:44,416
They become executable.

573
00:32:44,916 --> 00:32:47,346
I try to read a lot of books,
and this is one of them.

574
00:32:47,926 --> 00:32:51,356
This-- There's a term for this
in Building Evo-Evolutionary

575
00:32:51,356 --> 00:32:53,476
Architectures by Neal Ford and others.

576
00:32:53,976 --> 00:32:56,716
They call these checks
architecture fitness functions.

577
00:32:57,376 --> 00:33:01,886
The idea is this: if an architectural
property matters, like modularity

578
00:33:01,886 --> 00:33:05,626
or oscillation or direction of
dependencies, you should be able to test

579
00:33:05,626 --> 00:33:08,256
it, not just once, but continuously.

580
00:33:08,696 --> 00:33:11,536
If the test fails, the
architecture failed, even if

581
00:33:11,666 --> 00:33:13,236
all other unit tests are green.

582
00:33:13,736 --> 00:33:14,176
All right.

583
00:33:14,456 --> 00:33:15,896
All of this tooling is important.

584
00:33:16,295 --> 00:33:19,516
Next, let's talk about what
we learned from the pilot.

585
00:33:20,016 --> 00:33:20,326
All right.

586
00:33:20,666 --> 00:33:21,926
We completed the pilot.

587
00:33:22,536 --> 00:33:28,506
Not a proposal, not a design, actual code
running in production with real usage.

588
00:33:29,015 --> 00:33:34,395
A single bounded context, activity audit,
extracted from a ten-year monolith.

589
00:33:34,895 --> 00:33:35,346
Great.

590
00:33:35,846 --> 00:33:38,246
At that point, it stopped
being a question of intent.

591
00:33:38,555 --> 00:33:40,856
We could actually look at the results.

592
00:33:41,356 --> 00:33:42,946
And the answer is, it worked.

593
00:33:43,366 --> 00:33:46,276
Not in a clean, predictable
way we imagined at the start.

594
00:33:46,776 --> 00:33:51,116
It validated the direction, and it also
exposed a lot of things we didn't expect.

595
00:33:51,616 --> 00:33:55,276
Some parts become simpler, some
parts became clearer, and some parts

596
00:33:55,276 --> 00:33:58,595
became more complicated, which is
exactly what you want from a pilot.

597
00:33:59,066 --> 00:34:01,026
Not confirmation, but reality.

598
00:34:01,526 --> 00:34:04,826
What changed most was the discussion
stopped being theoretical.

599
00:34:05,406 --> 00:34:09,266
We were no longer debating whether bounded
context could exist in this code base.

600
00:34:09,646 --> 00:34:10,616
We had one.

601
00:34:10,786 --> 00:34:14,086
We could look at the package boundaries,
the imports, the tests, the CI

602
00:34:14,086 --> 00:34:15,415
workflow, the dependency wiring.

603
00:34:16,266 --> 00:34:17,696
That shifted the conversation.

604
00:34:17,735 --> 00:34:21,005
The problem was no longer
is modularization possible?

605
00:34:21,376 --> 00:34:26,216
Problem became, what patterns actually
hold up when you do it for real?

606
00:34:26,716 --> 00:34:29,266
One of the more interesting
outcomes was bugs.

607
00:34:30,136 --> 00:34:36,666
Refactoring did not just reduce risk,
it revealed risk that we already had.

608
00:34:37,286 --> 00:34:40,876
As we pulled the activity context
apart from the monolith, we

609
00:34:40,876 --> 00:34:45,226
started seeing assumptions- That
had never been made explicit.

610
00:34:45,646 --> 00:34:50,006
Rules that existed in our documentation,
but not consistently in code.

611
00:34:50,376 --> 00:34:53,546
Edge cases that had been
hidden inside legacy flows.

612
00:34:54,126 --> 00:34:59,726
In one case, we found we were violating
rollback access control rules, RBAC,

613
00:35:00,186 --> 00:35:01,876
that we had publicly documented.

614
00:35:02,376 --> 00:35:05,306
In another, we found an edge
case that cut against our claims

615
00:35:05,306 --> 00:35:06,636
of visibility and transparency.

616
00:35:07,296 --> 00:35:12,436
A canceled operation could end up
deleting past activity record, including

617
00:35:12,436 --> 00:35:14,486
who requested that original operation.

618
00:35:14,986 --> 00:35:17,196
And those were not new
bugs created by the pilot.

619
00:35:17,196 --> 00:35:22,116
They were old bugs that became easier
to see once the boundaries were clearer.

620
00:35:22,616 --> 00:35:26,876
That was one of the strongest signals that
this refactor was doing something real.

621
00:35:27,406 --> 00:35:29,226
It was not just moving files around.

622
00:35:29,456 --> 00:35:34,836
It was forcing the system to say more
precisely what the behavior actually was.

623
00:35:35,336 --> 00:35:39,326
Another strong signal that this approach
works came from something ordinary.

624
00:35:39,826 --> 00:35:42,656
This internal package, internal directory.

625
00:35:43,476 --> 00:35:48,386
Code outside that bound- boundary
simply cannot import the implementation.

626
00:35:48,886 --> 00:35:52,136
The boundary is this whole directory,
the se- service activity directory.

627
00:35:52,636 --> 00:35:55,696
So in Go, internal is
enforced by the compiler.

628
00:35:56,056 --> 00:36:01,696
If you could put code inside
it, nothing outside this part

629
00:36:01,696 --> 00:36:03,096
of the code base can import it.

630
00:36:03,686 --> 00:36:06,156
No conventions, no code review
rules, no "Please don't do

631
00:36:06,156 --> 00:36:08,086
this," it just fails to compile.

632
00:36:08,586 --> 00:36:11,956
Why I bring this up is because a
lot of architectural boundaries

633
00:36:11,956 --> 00:36:13,416
are softer than they look.

634
00:36:13,736 --> 00:36:17,746
They depend on engineers remembering
the rules, reviewers noticing

635
00:36:17,746 --> 00:36:21,106
violations, and everyone continuing
to agree on the structure.

636
00:36:21,836 --> 00:36:24,786
Internal removes that
entire class of failure.

637
00:36:25,206 --> 00:36:28,856
It means another bounded context cannot
reach into your service implementation

638
00:36:28,856 --> 00:36:30,016
just because it's convenient.

639
00:36:30,546 --> 00:36:33,206
It cannot pull your MySQL layer directly.

640
00:36:33,206 --> 00:36:35,966
It can't quietly start
depending on internals that

641
00:36:35,966 --> 00:36:37,236
were supposed to stay private.

642
00:36:37,736 --> 00:36:42,056
The compiler stops it, and in a large
code base, that's a big difference.

643
00:36:42,346 --> 00:36:45,456
At that po- point, the boundary is
no longer just something written

644
00:36:45,456 --> 00:36:49,736
in an ADR or drawn on a slide,
it is part of the program itself.

645
00:36:50,026 --> 00:36:51,756
You can't cross it accidentally.

646
00:36:52,256 --> 00:36:56,076
Another pattern that proved useful
was the bootstrap layer over here.

647
00:36:56,576 --> 00:37:01,706
Each bounded context has a single
entry point, a bootstrap.new function.

648
00:37:02,566 --> 00:37:05,836
That's the only place where
dependencies are wired together.

649
00:37:06,276 --> 00:37:09,326
From the outside, you don't see the
internal structure, you don't know

650
00:37:09,326 --> 00:37:13,626
about the database implementation of the
service internals, you just get a fully

651
00:37:13,626 --> 00:37:16,641
constructed Bounded context service.

652
00:37:17,361 --> 00:37:20,351
That sounds small, but it
simplifies a lot of things.

653
00:37:20,861 --> 00:37:25,311
Testing becomes easier, integration
becomes predictable, and r- it reinforces

654
00:37:25,311 --> 00:37:30,801
the idea that a bounded context is a
unit, not just a collection of packages.

655
00:37:31,301 --> 00:37:35,171
It gives us one consistent way to
instantiate the bounded context

656
00:37:35,351 --> 00:37:37,251
in both production and tests.

657
00:37:37,821 --> 00:37:39,441
That was a bigger deal than I expected.

658
00:37:39,851 --> 00:37:42,931
Without a single composition
root, dependency wiring tends to

659
00:37:42,931 --> 00:37:44,901
spread across the cal- codebase.

660
00:37:45,381 --> 00:37:48,661
Different entry points start assembling
slightly different versions of the same

661
00:37:48,661 --> 00:37:53,071
thing, and then it becomes harder to tell
whe- whether different environments are

662
00:37:53,071 --> 00:37:55,221
really exercising the same code path.

663
00:37:55,801 --> 00:37:59,131
Keeping that wiring in one place
removed a lot of that ambiguity.

664
00:37:59,631 --> 00:38:02,711
We introduced an anti-corruption
layer between the new context

665
00:38:02,771 --> 00:38:03,771
and the legacy system.

666
00:38:04,561 --> 00:38:08,281
Now, we covered this part earlier,
and this was the first time we

667
00:38:08,281 --> 00:38:09,981
applied it in this codebase.

668
00:38:10,631 --> 00:38:14,951
With the ACL, those calls moved
behind a single interface.

669
00:38:15,831 --> 00:38:21,641
That interface listed exactly what the
new bounded context depended on, right?

670
00:38:21,971 --> 00:38:27,061
We could point to methods, not
categories or concepts, actual functions.

671
00:38:27,691 --> 00:38:31,931
Most of them already existed in a legacy
system, but we also had to add a couple

672
00:38:31,931 --> 00:38:34,261
new methods to support this interface.

673
00:38:34,761 --> 00:38:36,041
That addition was useful.

674
00:38:36,261 --> 00:38:40,401
It forced us to be explicit
about a dependency that would

675
00:38:40,401 --> 00:38:42,361
have otherwise stayed implicit.

676
00:38:43,191 --> 00:38:46,341
At that point, the ACL became
easier to reason about.

677
00:38:46,751 --> 00:38:50,121
If you want to understand how this
context interacts with the rest of the

678
00:38:50,121 --> 00:38:52,481
system, you just read this interface.

679
00:38:53,231 --> 00:38:56,241
And it also gives us a
simple way to track progress.

680
00:38:56,811 --> 00:39:01,221
Every method in this ACL is a
dependency on the legacy system.

681
00:39:01,861 --> 00:39:03,861
Fewer methods means less coupling.

682
00:39:04,201 --> 00:39:07,441
More methods means the
boundary still needs some work.

683
00:39:07,941 --> 00:39:10,941
That interface gave us a much
clearer definition of done.

684
00:39:11,501 --> 00:39:14,431
The goal was not to build an
impressive ACL, the goal was

685
00:39:14,431 --> 00:39:16,711
keep that interface narrow.

686
00:39:17,231 --> 00:39:21,491
If the activity context needed five
or six methods from legacy code, fine.

687
00:39:22,051 --> 00:39:25,071
If it kept growing, that was a signal.

688
00:39:25,421 --> 00:39:28,831
Either the boundary was wrong or
we were still dragging too much

689
00:39:28,831 --> 00:39:30,781
of the monolith through that seam.

690
00:39:31,481 --> 00:39:35,151
In that sense, the ACL was not just
a bridge, it was a measurement point.

691
00:39:35,651 --> 00:39:39,410
We also changed how CI, continuous
integration, works for this code.

692
00:39:39,831 --> 00:39:43,840
Instead of running everything on every
change, the activity context has its

693
00:39:43,891 --> 00:39:46,541
own workflow, its own CI workflow.

694
00:39:46,910 --> 00:39:50,090
It only runs when files
in that context change.

695
00:39:50,590 --> 00:39:55,171
That had an effect on both sides
of the system For the new bounded

696
00:39:55,171 --> 00:39:57,041
context, the signal is clear.

697
00:39:57,261 --> 00:40:00,751
If something fails, it is in
the activity-bounded context.

698
00:40:01,091 --> 00:40:02,931
There's no ambiguity about where to look.

699
00:40:03,311 --> 00:40:05,561
For the legacy code base, it also helped.

700
00:40:06,261 --> 00:40:10,831
We removed activity-related tests from
the main test suite, so the remaining

701
00:40:10,831 --> 00:40:15,191
tests run slightly faster, and there's
less noise from unrelated failures.

702
00:40:15,691 --> 00:40:19,091
That separation is small but
noticeable, and more importantly,

703
00:40:19,091 --> 00:40:20,730
it reflects the architecture.

704
00:40:21,331 --> 00:40:25,330
The code is split, and now the
feedback loops are split as well.

705
00:40:25,830 --> 00:40:28,250
That sounds operational,
but it changed behavior.

706
00:40:28,640 --> 00:40:32,880
When the team sees a failure tied
to its own context, ownership is

707
00:40:32,880 --> 00:40:37,040
clear, and when unrelated failures
stop showing up in the same workflow,

708
00:40:37,290 --> 00:40:39,620
people spend less time triaging noise.

709
00:40:40,180 --> 00:40:43,270
The architecture becomes visible
not just in the code layout,

710
00:40:43,530 --> 00:40:45,540
but in the daily developer loop.

711
00:40:46,040 --> 00:40:48,050
We also added architecture tests.

712
00:40:48,500 --> 00:40:51,260
They define which packages
are allowed to import which.

713
00:40:51,760 --> 00:40:53,940
Each bounded context has an allow list.

714
00:40:54,310 --> 00:40:57,950
If a package pulls in something
outside that list, the test fails.

715
00:40:58,630 --> 00:41:01,191
That check runs in CI
just like any other test.

716
00:41:01,521 --> 00:41:05,981
So if someone or an AI agent
introduces a new dependency across

717
00:41:05,981 --> 00:41:08,161
a boundary, it shows up immediately.

718
00:41:08,711 --> 00:41:11,920
There's no need to catch it in
a review, and it doesn't rely

719
00:41:11,920 --> 00:41:13,871
on people remembering the rules.

720
00:41:14,231 --> 00:41:16,211
The constraint is in the code.

721
00:41:16,711 --> 00:41:21,641
Taken together, internal, the ACL,
the bootstrap layer, the dedicated

722
00:41:21,641 --> 00:41:25,331
CI workflow, and the architecture
tests did something important.

723
00:41:25,681 --> 00:41:30,411
They turned the bounded context from
simply a clean directory structure

724
00:41:30,411 --> 00:41:34,031
into something we could enforce,
test, and operate separately.

725
00:41:34,811 --> 00:41:39,411
That is a much stronger result
than, "The code looks nicer." But

726
00:41:39,451 --> 00:41:42,581
it's important to be clear about
what this pilot did not solve.

727
00:41:43,321 --> 00:41:45,091
We did not modularize the system.

728
00:41:45,691 --> 00:41:47,751
We modularized a small part of it.

729
00:41:48,251 --> 00:41:49,941
Most of the monolith is still there.

730
00:41:50,311 --> 00:41:52,051
Most boundaries are still undefined.

731
00:41:52,431 --> 00:41:55,601
We still have shared concepts
that don't map cleanly to a single

732
00:41:55,601 --> 00:42:00,451
context, and we still have open
questions about how these contexts

733
00:42:00,451 --> 00:42:02,611
will interact as the system grows.

734
00:42:03,421 --> 00:42:05,101
So this is not a finished architecture.

735
00:42:05,431 --> 00:42:07,021
It is a validated direction.

736
00:42:07,521 --> 00:42:09,511
Where we are now is
somewhere in the middle.

737
00:42:10,111 --> 00:42:13,251
We've completed one bounded
context, and now we're figuring

738
00:42:13,251 --> 00:42:15,151
out how to do the next ones.

739
00:42:15,891 --> 00:42:18,581
The next likely candidates are
user management and certificate

740
00:42:18,581 --> 00:42:20,521
management, and those are harder.

741
00:42:20,881 --> 00:42:24,091
Activity was a good pilot because
it was more self-contained.

742
00:42:24,681 --> 00:42:28,671
User management and certificate management
sit closer to the center of the system.

743
00:42:29,121 --> 00:42:32,191
They touch more workflows, more
teams, and more legacy code.

744
00:42:32,781 --> 00:42:37,641
So the next phase is not just repeating
what we already did, it is applying

745
00:42:37,641 --> 00:42:41,021
the same ideas in parts of the
monolith where the boundaries are less

746
00:42:41,021 --> 00:42:43,386
obvious and the coupling is heavier.

747
00:42:43,886 --> 00:42:45,486
But the uncertainty is different now.

748
00:42:45,876 --> 00:42:48,266
We're no longer asking
whether this can work.

749
00:42:48,596 --> 00:42:49,476
We've seen it work.

750
00:42:49,866 --> 00:42:54,546
Now the problem is scaling it carefully
without breaking what already exists.

751
00:42:55,046 --> 00:42:55,506
All right.

752
00:42:56,006 --> 00:42:58,846
Let's circle back to the core
problem we're trying to solve.

753
00:42:59,346 --> 00:43:02,046
Looking back, the real
constraint wasn't Go.

754
00:43:02,546 --> 00:43:03,586
It wasn't MySQL.

755
00:43:03,756 --> 00:43:05,116
It wasn't even the monolith.

756
00:43:05,506 --> 00:43:07,606
The real constraint was human attention.

757
00:43:08,166 --> 00:43:11,746
How much of the system can
one people hold in their head?

758
00:43:12,266 --> 00:43:14,766
How much confidently
can they make a change?

759
00:43:14,996 --> 00:43:18,906
And how much unrelated context they
have to load just to get started?

760
00:43:19,406 --> 00:43:24,115
Once a system grows beyond that
limit, progress slows, no matter

761
00:43:24,115 --> 00:43:25,825
how good the engineers are.

762
00:43:26,325 --> 00:43:29,295
We often talk about architecture
as if it's for computers.

763
00:43:29,555 --> 00:43:32,475
But computers don't care
how big your code base is.

764
00:43:32,905 --> 00:43:33,615
Humans do.

765
00:43:34,145 --> 00:43:36,745
Architecture is really
an interface for people.

766
00:43:36,935 --> 00:43:41,325
It defines what you need to understand,
what you can safely ignore, and

767
00:43:41,325 --> 00:43:42,685
what you're allowed to change.

768
00:43:43,156 --> 00:43:47,305
When that interface is unclear,
every change feels risky.

769
00:43:47,605 --> 00:43:51,575
When it's clear, people move
faster, even in a large system.

770
00:43:52,075 --> 00:43:55,585
The tricky part is that this
problem shows up after success.

771
00:43:56,255 --> 00:44:00,465
The monolith works, the product
ships, customers are happy, and

772
00:44:00,465 --> 00:44:05,905
slowly, almost invisibly, the
system becomes harder to change.

773
00:44:06,725 --> 00:44:08,625
We're not fixing a broken system.

774
00:44:08,895 --> 00:44:12,575
We're fixing a system that
worked until it didn't.

775
00:44:13,385 --> 00:44:16,565
That's why these conversations are
hard, and that's why they matter.

776
00:44:17,065 --> 00:44:18,905
We knew our system had grown too complex.

777
00:44:19,355 --> 00:44:23,125
Not complex in an abstract
sense, complex in a human sense.

778
00:44:23,506 --> 00:44:26,576
It had grown beyond what a human
brain could comfortably hold.

779
00:44:27,105 --> 00:44:30,385
Every small change required
understanding too much at once.

780
00:44:31,045 --> 00:44:34,916
At that point, adding rules or
documentation doesn't fix the problem.

781
00:44:35,195 --> 00:44:37,475
You have to change the
shape of the system.

782
00:44:37,975 --> 00:44:42,815
For a long time, I thought the hard part
was architecture, or code, or tooling.

783
00:44:43,105 --> 00:44:43,675
It wasn't.

784
00:44:44,165 --> 00:44:47,085
The hardest part was
alignment with other humans.

785
00:44:47,505 --> 00:44:50,715
Shared language, shared
understanding, shared ownership.

786
00:44:51,215 --> 00:44:54,025
Code changes fast, especially
now with AI agents.

787
00:44:54,625 --> 00:44:58,775
Architecture survives only when
people agree to carry it together.

788
00:44:59,275 --> 00:45:00,425
We don't have a clean ending.

789
00:45:00,515 --> 00:45:01,805
The work is still moving.

790
00:45:01,845 --> 00:45:03,815
Boundaries are still being uncovered.

791
00:45:03,845 --> 00:45:05,405
Edge cases are still surfacing.

792
00:45:05,815 --> 00:45:07,685
But something important has shifted.

793
00:45:07,965 --> 00:45:12,455
The system is starting to feel smaller,
more defined, easier to follow.

794
00:45:12,945 --> 00:45:15,935
And for the first time in a long
time, the code base is helping us

795
00:45:15,935 --> 00:45:17,855
think instead of getting in the way.

796
00:45:18,355 --> 00:45:20,995
So if there's one thing I hope you
take away from this talk, it's this.

797
00:45:21,755 --> 00:45:24,835
Modularization isn't really about modules.

798
00:45:25,135 --> 00:45:27,895
It's about respecting the
limits of human attention.

799
00:45:28,375 --> 00:45:31,415
It's about designing systems
that people can understand,

800
00:45:31,465 --> 00:45:33,555
trust, and change without fear.

801
00:45:34,195 --> 00:45:38,076
Tools matter, patterns matter, but
architecture lasts only when it's

802
00:45:38,125 --> 00:45:39,805
owned by more than one person.

803
00:45:40,305 --> 00:45:41,345
That's it for this talk.

804
00:45:42,205 --> 00:45:45,155
If this resonated with you, I'd
be interested to hear from you.

805
00:45:45,195 --> 00:45:47,715
How are you approaching similar
problems in your own systems?

806
00:45:48,635 --> 00:45:50,735
Details are different, but
the patterns usually aren't.

807
